name: R for Data Science Workshop: Data Wrangling in the Tidyverse
description:
This is the third meetup in a series of six workshops to work through the book R for Data Science by Hadley Wickham and Garrett Grolemund. Please bring a laptop with R Studio and R loaded up. (Let us know if you have questions or need help getting that set up.)

We'll be covering these chapters:
+ Tibbles with tibble
+ Data Import with readr
+ Tidy data with tidyr
+ Relational data with dplyr
+ Strings with stringr
+ Factors with forcats
+ Dates and Times with lubridate

Agenda
+ 6:30 - 7pm : Dinner and Networking
+ 7 - 8:30pm : Workshop

name: Building Interactive Plots with Shiny
description:
WHAT WE'RE DOING:

This event will be a mix of socializing and trying out Shiny. Shiny is an R package that makes it easy to build interactive web apps straight from R. You can host standalone apps on a webpage or embed them in R Markdown documents or build dashboards. Â  Here's an example of a Shiny app from David Robinson (the stats guy, not the basketball player).

WHAT TO BRING:

Bring your laptop. Your laptop cord and a notebook might be a good idea, too. If you can, try to install R and the Shiny package before coming.

CONSUMING THINGS:

Just down the hall is a mini coffee shop (open til 8PM). Feel free to bring snackies or beverages.

LOCATION:

We have a classroom for this meetup! Meet us in room 226 of O'Shaughnessy Science. This is the building connected to Owens science. You can park on Summit for free. The parking ramp is also convenient and decently priced ($1.00 or $1.50 per hour). The east side of the building has an elevator and the building is generally accessible.

VOLUNTEERS:

Kim Ky and Becca will be creating some basicÂ  examples to teach us how Shiny works.
how_to_find_us: Room 226 in OSS. OSS is on Cretin between Grand and Summit.

name: Beginner Statistic workshop in R
description:
Beginner Statistic workshop in R

Speaker: Navid Nobani

In this workshop you will learn what is statistics, how it can be useful for data analysis and why as a data scientist you need to learn it. The topics are fundamental concepts, and are focused on:

- What are variable types in data and how to deal with them


- How to measure variability and central tendency of data

- How to choose graphical presentation types based on types of variables


- Linear & regression modeling

Language: Examples & exercises will be in R

Prerequisites: Having laptop is not mandatory

Target Audience: Beginners level

Bio: Navid is a data scientist at Prometeon Tyre Group. He has a background in Industrial Engineering and is working in the data science field since 2015. He uses R and Python in his daily activities to solve business problems in the marketing area.


If you are interested, donâ€™t hesitate to join us & spread the event to your friends too. We are looking forward to meet up with you!
how_to_find_us: Please go to the reception and give your document and get a badge. I'll be there at 18.50 and we go to the classroom together.

name: Linear, Logistic, and Cox Regression: When and How to Run in RStudio
description:
Join us to learn about regression in RStudio. This month's meet up will be led by Jacqueline Kueper, PhD candidate in Epidemiology and Biostatistics at Western.

No previous experience with regression or RStudio is required; all abilities are welcome. The main portion of the session will involve step-by-step instructions on how to set up, run, and interpret results from regression models that include one and more than one independent variable. We will also cover some background on three types of regressionâ€”linear, logistic, and Coxâ€”including when and why you might want to run each of these models. Sample code and data will be made available so that you can follow along on a personal laptop; sitting back to absorb the conversation in a more hands-off way is also an option.

Get excited! See you in December!
how_to_find_us: We are in the Wellington Room, on the second floor at the back. Parking under the library (entrance on King St) can be validated for up to 2 hours at the library help desk.

name: Intro to dplyr & ggplot2 with Marieke Jones
description:
* Updated Location * Please note that we will be meeting at Hemoshear, not VividCortex. Hemoshear is located near the other end of the Downtown Mall at 501 Locust Avenue, Suite 301. There is free parking in the parking lot.Â 

Pipes, plots, and more!Â 

Join us for a two-part workshop led by UVA's Marieke Jones on two core packages in the tidyverse: dplyr and ggplot2. This session is geared towards all proficiency levels in R. Whether you've just started learning and you want to know what piping is or how to make a plot, or if you're a pro and you want a refresher on writing cleaner code, this workshop will be beneficial to you. Also, there will be pizza :)

Schedule:

â€¢Â 6:00-6:45 Intro to R

â€¢Â 6:45-7:30 Intro to dplyrÂ 

Come to one or both!Â 

Please bring a laptop with R, RStudio, and the tidyverse package installed before coming to the MeetUp. If you need a short tutorial on getting oriented in R and on installing a package in R, please see this YouTube video.Â We will be available 30min before the session starts to assist anyone with troubles installing R, RStudio, or packages.

Please download the nhanes.csv dataset we will be using during the sessions. Save this file to your Desktop so you can easily find it.Â 

Follow us on twitter for more updates! @RLadiesCville

See you then!

name: Kick-starting R-Ladies Vancouver!!!!
description:
Hello R-Ladies community!


We are ready to kick-start our Vancouver chapter of the R-Ladies!


Come along to this introductory event where we will discuss the mission of R-Ladies, goals of our chapter and get to know each other. This event is kindly supported by Hothead Games, who are hosting us at their office downtown, thanks a bunch Hothead Games! Also, shout-out to RStudio for providing the food. Space is limited so please make sure you RSVP to get your spot.


If you havenâ€™t done so yet, please fill out this survey to help us organize future events: https://goo.gl/forms/oztMH7oj0bcKHFUq1


Here is a tentative agenda. Times may shift depending on how many folks show up and what you are interested in sharing.


Â 6:00-6:15 pm - Arriving/networking


Â 6:15 pm: Introduction; a presentation with a discussion on:

Â â€¢ What is R-Ladies?

Â â€¢ What would we like to see at R-Ladies events

Â â€¢ Share your comments about location for future meetups

Â â€¢ Any other R-Ladies Vancouver issues you would like to discuss email: vancouver@rladies.org


7:00 pm - Lightning talks or an R related talk (depending on interest)


Lightning talks - this is an opportunity to informally introduce ourselves and share what we are using R for or what we are hoping to do with R (~ 5-10 minutes each). If you would like to give a little talk, here's a link to sign up HERE.There is no need for fancy slides (or any slides), the idea is to share our R interests/backgrounds and for the members to get to know each other.

name: R-Ladies Launch with Hadley Wickham
description:
Hi Everyone!


We are thrilled to announce our meetup launch with Hadley Wickham presenting an introduction to the tidyverse.Â 

This will aimed all all R abilities. For thoseÂ very new to R or those who have using the tidyverse for a while, you'll still pick up some new tricks.

Bio:Â 
Hadley is Chief Scientist at RStudio, a member of the R Foundation, and Adjunct Professor at Stanford University and the University of Auckland. He builds tools (both computational and cognitive) to make data science easier, faster, and more fun. His work includes packages for data science (the tidyverse: including ggplot2, dplyr, tidyr, purrr, and readr) and principled software development (roxygen2,Â 
testthat, devtools). He is also a writer, educator, and speaker promoting the use of R for data science. Learn more on his website,Â http://hadley.nzÂ .


This meetup is being run in conjunction with the Data Science Discussion groupÂ https://www.meetup.com/Data-Science-Discussion-Auckland/


We look forward to meeting you.

R-Ladies Auckland.

name: Rise & Shiny - Interactive Maps (Leaflet)
description:
December Rise & Shiny will cover topics in Interactive Maps and how to use the Leaflet package/framework in Shiny apps. We're going to try a slightly different format this month: less "lecture" tutorial, and more "choose your own adventure" tutorial. Our goal will be to publish tutorial material on Friday night, before the workshop, so that you can get a sense for what part or sections you might like to try working through on Saturday morning.

Topics of Interest:
- The leaflet package
- R packages for extending leaflet
- GeoJSON (what is it / how to create it)
- Alternatives to leaflet
- Github and shinyapps.io
- Coffee and Muffins!

Thanks as always to our sponsor, B23 - platform.b23.io

This event is open to all members of the RStats community who support our mission of increasing gender diversity in tech. If this is your first meetup with us, please take a moment to read our code of conduct before committing to attend.

name: Kick-off Meeting
description:
R-Ladies Leuven is now officially alive and kicking! And to celebrate we are organizing our first kick-off meeting to shape the future ofÂ our chapter. In this meeting, we will introduce R-Ladies and R-Ladies Leuven, we will get to know each other, and we will discuss how we want to shape future events in our community.Â 


Schedule:

5:30pm - Doors open

5:45pm - Welcome and introduction to R-Ladies and R-Ladies Leuven (who we are!)

Remember that the stated priority of the R-Ladies communities is the development & support specifically of those identifying as female. However, due to unexpected demand, we have opened learning participation to all genders, provided everybody respects the guidelines of our code of conduct. So feel free to come and join!

name: R in the world of Education
description:
We are very excited to announce our last meetup of the year with Erin Grand.

Her Talk:Â Many schools across the country are starting to use data to help improve student outcomes. In this talk,Â ErinÂ will discuss what kind of data she gets to dive into and some of the challenges each project faces. She'll talk about ways to clean messy data, how using R has helped speed up everything, and the amazing janitor package.

Her Bio: Â ErinÂ joined Uncommon Schools as an Associate Director of Data Analytics in the summer of 2016. Prior to Uncommon, she worked as a DataÂ Scientist at Crisis Text Line and a software programmer at NASA. She recently completed her mastersÂ in Data Science at Columbia University. In the past,Â ErinÂ researched star formation and taught introductory courses in astronomy and physics. In her free time,Â ErinÂ enjoys reading, dancing and singing loudly to musical theatre.

name: New year, new R meetup!
description:
Ring in the new year with a resolution to use R more!

Who are we? We are a few women in Philadelphia who use R and wanted to have a friendly community to extend our R skills and network with other women R users. We learned about the international R-Ladies community and decided to try it in our city.

Anyone with an interest in R is welcome. You can be an R expert or novice.

When? This January will be the first meeting. We plan to have an informal mixer to introduce ourselves and find out what topics are of the most interest for future meetings. After this first meeting, we hope to start a monthly schedule of interactive workshops led by volunteers. If you have anything you want to share, a problem you are working on, or an idea for a collaborative project, we want to hear about it!

If you are completely new to R, bring your computer, and we can walk you through setting up R and RStudio or answer any setup questions you have been working through.

Where? We are being hosted at MakeOffices in center city. There will be snacks (details TBD)

In this fun, informal setting, participants have approximately 3 to 5 minutes to speak about their research, work, or a puzzle they're trying to solve - anything goes as long as it involves R! Prepare a brief presentation and a visual or two (slide, code snippets, graph, etc). Come share your work, learn what your peers are up to, and exchange ideas! If you would like to present, fill out our questionnaire before December 23, if you would like to attend please RSVP at our MeetUp page by January 23. Thanks!

name: Lightening Talks
description:
Come join the R-Ladies in our first ever Lightening Talks event. In this fun, informal setting, participants have approximately 3 to 5 minutes to speak about their research, work, or a puzzle they're trying to solve - anything goes! R-related presentations are a bonus but not necessary! Our goal is to 1) provide a space to learn about the others in our community and 2) exchange ideas about methodologies, interests, and the tools we all are using.

IMPORTANT:

In addition to RSVPing on our MeetUp page, please ALSO complete this form by December 23 to help us with scheduling and to let us know important pieces of information.

This is not meant to be a high-stakes presentation event - just a chance to share our projects with each other and learn a little about the questions each of us are asking in our own work and the tools we're using to answer them. As usual, we will head out for food and drinks following the event (drinks and apps for presenters are on us!)

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

NB: Please note that, in keeping with the global R-Ladies mission, R-Ladies London, Ontario will prioritize female leadership and participation. All interested people (regardless of gender) are welcome to RSVP to our events. However, in the event that we receive a greater amount of presenter interest than we feel is manageable for the space/time, we will prioritize female presenters.
